4. [type 2 diabetes](!Wikipedia)

    [Morris et al 2012](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3442244/ "Large-scale association analysis provides insights into the genetic architecture and pathophysiology of type 2 diabetes")'s [supplementary information](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3442244/bin/NIHMS393294-supplement-2.pdf) reports a polygenic score predicting 5.73% on liability scale.

    Diabetes is not a continuous trait like IQ/height/BMI, but generally treated as a binary disease: you either have good blood sugar control and will not go blind and suffer all the other morbidity caused by diabetes, or you don't. The underlying genetics is still highly polygenic and mostly additive, though, and in some sense one's risk is normally distributed. The liability scale threshold model is the usual model for dealing with binary variables like this: one's risk is a normal variable (which is the sum of many individual genes), and when one is unlucky enough for this risk to be enough standard deviations out past a threshold, one has the disease. The enough standard deviations is set empirically; if 1% of the population will develop schizophrenia, then one has to be +2.33SD out to develop schizophrenia, and assuming a mean risk of 0, one can then calculate the effects of an increase or decrease. For example, if some change results in decreasing one's risk score 1SD such that it would takes another 3.33SD to develop schizophrenia, then one's probability of developing schizophrenia has decreased from 1% to 0.04%, a fall of 23x (`pnorm(qnorm(0.01)) / pnorm(qnorm(0.01)-1) ~> 22.73`) and so whatever one estimated the expected loss of schizophrenia at, it has decreased 23x and the change of 1SD can be valued at that.

    Similarly for diabetes. We can estimate the NPV of not developing diabetes at as much as [\$124,600 (NPV)](http://care.diabetesjournals.org/content/37/9/2557.full); the lifetime risk of diabetes in the USA is [approaching ~40%](http://jama.jamanetwork.com/article.aspx?articleid=197439 "'Lifetime Risk for Diabetes Mellitus in the United States', Narayan et al 2003") and has probably exceeded it by now (implying, incidentally, that diabetes is one of the most costly diseases in the world), so the expected loss is \$49840 and developing diabetes has a threshold of 0.39SD; a decrease of 1SD gives one a third less chance of developing diabetes (`pnorm(qnorm(0.40)-1) / pnorm(qnorm(0.40)) ~> 0.26`) for a savings of \$11k (`(124600 * 0.4) - (124600 * 0.4 * 0.26) ~> 36881`); finally, \$36.8k/SD, compared with IQ, gets a weight of 15%.
5. [ADHD](!Wikipedia)

    ADHD polygenic scores range from [0.098%](http://adhdnet.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Hamshere-2013-High-loading-of-polygenic.pdf "'High Loading of Polygenic Risk for ADHD in Children With Comorbid Aggression', Hamshere et al 2013")/[0.4%](http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0890856715000404 "'Shared Genetic Influences Between Attention-Deficit/Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD) Traits in Children and Clinical ADHD', Stergiakouli et al 2015")/[0.5%](http://adhdnet.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Groen-Blokhuis-2014-ADHD-Polygenic-risk-scores.pdf  "'Attention-Deficit/Hyperactivity Disorder Polygenic Risk Scores Predict Attention Problems in a Population-Based Sample of Children', Groen-Blokhuis et al 2014")/[0.59%](http://bjp.rcpsych.org/content/203/2/107.full "'Shared polygenic contribution between childhood attention-deficit hyperactivity disorder and adult schizophrenia', Hamshere et al 2013")/[1.5%](http://www.nature.com/tp/journal/v5/n2/full/tp20155a.html "'The relative contribution of common and rare genetic variants to ADHD', Martin et al 2015").
    Prevalence rates differ based on country & diagnosis method, but most genetics studies were run using DSM diagnoses in the West, so ~7% of children affected.
    [Biederman & Faraone 2006](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1781280/ "The Effects of Attention-Deficit/Hyperactivity Disorder on Employment and Household Income") find large harmful correlations, estimating a -\$8900 annual loss from ADHD or ~\$182k NPV.
    So the best score is 1.5%; the liability threshold is 1.47SD; the starting expected loss is ~\$12768; a 1SD reduction is then worth \$11.5k (`182000*pnorm(qnorm(0.07)) - 182000*pnorm(qnorm(0.07)-1) ~> 115304`) and has a weight of 4.7%.
